    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-12-02T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-12-02T08:00:00-05:00" n="322"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                <head>322. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Greece</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d322fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 375/12–261. Confidential; Priority. Repeated to Paris <gloss
                            target="#t_TOPOL1">Topol</gloss>, Rome, and Ankara.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Athens</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-12-02T15:00:00+02:00">December 2, 1961, 3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>699. Paris for <gloss target="#t_USRO1">USRO</gloss>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_SWJJ1">Stoessel</persName> and McGuire. Rome for Rood. Main
                    Greek effort in connection <persName corresp="#p_SD1">Stikker</persName>
                        visit<note n="1" xml:id="d322fn1">
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Secretary General <persName
                            corresp="#p_SD1">Dirk Stikker</persName> visited Athens December 2 for
                        discussions relating to <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>’s scheduled
                        spring Ministerial Meeting. During his visit, the Greek Government outlined
                        its case for further military aid. The Embassy reported on the <persName
                            corresp="#p_SD1">Stikker</persName> visit in airgram A–296, December 2.
                        (Ibid.)</note> was to emphasize crucial nature Greek need for continuing
                    external aid order support its military effort. Pointed to low per capita
                    income, import-export imbalance. Estimated aid of $35 million more aid required
                    annually beyond present levels.</p>
                <p>Greeks pushed idea of <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> multilateral special
                    fund to make up deficiencies national military budgets. <persName
                        corresp="#p_SD1">Stikker</persName> responded cautiously. Foreign Office
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Director reports Averoff intends
                    approach Secretary in Paris to solicit his support multilateral fund idea, and
                    that Averoff will push for it at <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>
                    meeting.</p>
                <p>Airgram follows.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Briggs</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
